{
  "doc_id": "19990",
  "text": "The process of sintering has three stages: an initial, intermediate, and final stage [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . In the initial stage, the CPP green body has a low-density and is generally lacking in physical integrity. There is a small degree of adhesion between adjacent particles. Then, the necks begin to form at the contact points between the particles in the intermediate stage (Fig.2) . The final stage of sintering begins when most of the pores are closed. As shown in 3 shows the relative density and grain size influenced by the sintering time. The average CPP grain size increased monotonously in the range of 1.59-3.40 μm with increase of the sintering time. Meanwhile, the relative density ranged from 70.5% for the sample sintered for 30 minutes, to 79.4% for the sample sintered for 5 hours. These results indicate that the microstructure is more dense for a longer sintering time and the average grain size increased with increase of the sintering time, that corresponded to SEM results.",
